421 East 61st Street, north side, between York and First Aves., showing the Col. Smith House (also known as the Adams Mansion). This house was built in 1799 by Colonel Smith, a son-in-law of President Adams. One version states that it was built in 1777 by Peter Pra Van Sairt for a stable to his residence and he sold (1795) the mansion, stables and other buildings to Col. Wm. S. Smith. The latter failed in business and his stable became a tavern and was used as such until 1830 when Jeremiah Fowle purchased it, whose daughter occupied it until 1906. The Consolidated Gas Company sold this building in December 1924 to the Colonial Dames. This set consists of 4 views taken at the same time.

February 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(1)

421 East 61st Street, north side, between York and First Aves. This house was built in 1790 as a wedding gift to one of John Adams' daughters. At the time of this picture it is occupied by the Museum of the City of New York. In 1931, however, the Museum will move uptown to its new building on the east side of Fifth Avenue from 103rd to 104th Streets, and this house will be occupied by the Colonial Dames of America.
September 15, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

The same, more of a side view.
September 15, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)

The same, six years later.
March 5, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
